        <div class="main_container">
            <%- include('partials/header.ejs') %>
        
            <div class="maincontent">
                <section>
                    <h2>Feeding</h2>
                    <p>
                        Provide your cat with a balanced diet formulated for their age, size, and 
                        health needs. Offer high-quality cat food, either dry kibble or wet food, and ensure 
                        access to clean water at all times. Follow feeding guidelines provided by your 
                        veterinarian or the food packaging.
                    </p>
                </section>
                <section>
                    <h2>Grooming</h2>
                    <p>
                        Cats groom themselves regularly, but they may need assistance with 
                        brushing to remove loose hair and prevent hairballs, especially for long-haired breeds. 
                        Trim their nails as needed and clean their ears and teeth regularly to prevent 
                        infections and dental issues.
                    </p>
                </section>
                <section>
                    <h2>Litter Box Maintenance</h2>
                    <p>
                        Provide a clean and accessible litter box for your cat. Scoop 
                        the litter box daily to remove waste and clumps, and replace the litter entirely every 
                        few weeks. Ensure the litter box is located in a quiet, private area away from their food 
                        and water bowls.
                    </p>
                </section>
                <section>
                    <h2>Exercise and Play</h2>
                    <p>
                        Encourage regular play and exercise to keep your cat mentally and 
                        physically stimulated. Provide toys, scratching posts, and interactive play sessions to 
                        mimic hunting behaviors and prevent boredom.
                    </p>
                </section>
                <section>
                    <h2>Training and Socialization</h2>
                    <p>
                        While cats may not be as trainable as dogs, you can still 
                        teach them basic commands and behaviors using positive reinforcement techniques. 
                        Socialize your cat with people and other animals to help them feel more comfortable 
                        in different environments.
                    </p>
                </section>
                <section>
                    <h2>Healthcare</h2>
                    <p>
                        Schedule regular veterinary check-ups to monitor your cat's health and 
                        address any concerns. Keep up with vaccinations, parasite prevention (fleas, ticks, 
                        worms), and dental care. Spay or neuter your cat if not intending to breed to prevent 
                        unwanted litters and certain health issues.
                    </p>
                </section>
                <section>
                    <h2>Safety</h2>
                    <p>
                        Ensure your home is safe for your cat by removing hazards such as toxic 
                        plants, small objects they could swallow, and inaccessible areas where they could get 
                        stuck. Use a collar with identification tags and consider microchipping for added 
                        identification in case your cat gets lost.
                    </p>
                </section>
                <section>
                    <h2>Love and Attention</h2>
                    <p>
                        Cats thrive on companionship and affection, but they also value 
                        their independence. Spend quality time with your cat, offering gentle petting, cuddles, 
                        and interactive play. Respect their boundaries and provide opportunities for alone 
                        time when needed.
                    </p>
                </section>
                <section>
                    <h2>In The End</h2>
                    <p>
                        By following these guidelines and providing a loving and enriching environment, you can ensure your cat's health and happiness for years to come. If you have specific questions or concerns about caring for your cat, consult with your veterinarian for personalized advice.
                    </p>
                </section>
            </div>
            
